        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-11-13T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-11-13T01:00:00-05:00" n="404"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d404">
                <head>404. Telegram From the Ambassador in Vietnam (<persName corresp="#p_DE1"
                        type="from">Durbrow</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in
                        Cambodia</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d404fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 033.51G91/11–1357. Confidential. Repeated for information to the
                        Department of State, New Delhi, and Vientiane. The source text is the
                        Department copy.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1957-11-13T13:00:00+07:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 13, 1957—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>180. <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> reports <persName
                        corresp="#p_NPJ1">Nehru</persName> brought up question <gloss
                        target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_RKG1">RKG</gloss>
                        relations.<note n="2" xml:id="d404fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> visited India November
                        4–9.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> told <persName corresp="#p_NPJ1"
                        >Nehru</persName>: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>He had not massed troops but only maintained sufficient police and
                            troops to try control stepped-up terrorist acts in delta area.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_VN1">VN</gloss> has too many other problems to solve
                            ever to think of attacking Cambodia.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Frontier and dissident problem could be solved if <gloss
                                target="#t_RKG1">RKG</gloss> officials would cooperate with <gloss
                                target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> officials in operations liquidate
                            dissidents.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_SN1">Sihanouk</persName> doing nothing to organize
                            effective government or for economic development.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_SN1">Sihanouk</persName> only playing demagogic
                            role by inventing <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> military menace in
                            order distract public attention from their bad economic
                            situation.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_RKG1">RKG</gloss> not trying prevent Viet
                                <persName>Minh</persName> elements infiltrate from north to cause
                            trouble in <gloss target="#t_VN1">VN</gloss>.</item>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>If nothing done to build up strong government <gloss target="#t_RKG1"
                                >RKG</gloss> and take effective steps toward economic development in
                            the next two years there would be successful revolution organized by
                            Communists.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NPJ1">Nehru</persName> showed much interest in these
                    reports and promised to do what he could to rectify the situation. While
                        <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> encouraged <persName
                        corresp="#p_NPJ1">Nehru</persName> he did not have high hopes for effective
                    action. Details by pouch.<note n="3" xml:id="d404fn3">In despatch 172 from
                        Saigon, November 19 (Department of State, Central Files,
                        751G.11/11–1957)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DE1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Durbrow</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
